Super Bowl Ratings
------------------

From Variety ( https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/super-bowl-2025-ratings-vie=
wers-1236302721/ ) :

After finalized data came in from Nielsen, the total number of average view=
ers for Super Bowl LIX rose to 127.7 million, a 3% increase on 2024=E2=80=
=99s 123.7 million that further cements the game=E2=80=99s status as the bi=
ggest TV audience of all time. Additionally, Fox reports that average viewe=
rship during Kendrick Lamar=E2=80=99s halftime show was even higher, reachi=
ng 133.5 million =E2=80=94 another all-time high, improving by 3% on the 12=
9.3 million viewers achieved by Usher=E2=80=99s halftime show in 2024. The =
adjusted total for the most-watched piece of the telecast =E2=80=94 from 8 =
to 8:15 p.m. ET, during the second quarter of the game =E2=80=94 is 137.7 m=
illion viewers, up from the initially reported 135.7 million.

I thought one of the sharpest and most thought-provoking observations about=
 the Super Bowl specifically, and football broadly, came from Derek Thompso=
n on X ( https://x.com/DKThomp/status/1888258690127450458 ) :

( https://x.com/DKThomp/status/1888258690127450458 ) ( https://x.com/DKThom=
p/status/1888286048125596156 )

For those not in the weeds of the NBA, the Don=C4=8Di=C4=87 angle is partic=
ularly interesting, because it was Mavs minority owner Mark Cuban (who sure=
ly must be regretting giving up control of the team) who said a decade ago =
( https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/10662203/dallas-mavericks-owner-mark-=
cuban-says-greedy-nfl-10-years-away-implosion ) :

"I think the NFL is 10 years away from an implosion," Cuban said Sunday eve=
ning when his pregame conversation with reporters, which covered a broad ra=
nge of topics, swayed toward football. "I'm just telling you: Pigs get fat,=
 hogs get slaughtered. And they're getting hoggy"=E2=80=A6Cuban was specifi=
cally referring to the NFL's recently expanding its television package. He =
considers it a poor business decision for the NFL, which consistently domin=
ates TV ratings, to play games on days other than Sunday and Monday.

In fact, what seems clear is that the NFL has kept the main thing the main =
thing: what matters most is the games, the television rights to which are t=
he foundation of the sport's business model. The NFL was once mocked endles=
sly for cracking down on highlight sharing on social media, but what is the=
 point of social media highlights if they don't translate into eyeballs on =
TV screens? On the flipside, how does it benefit the NBA to be talked about=
 endlessly if no one is watching the games? The league's thirst for social =
media and cultural relevance =E2=80=94 none of which pays the bills =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0was the actual piggish behavior.

There are lots of other things going in the NFL's favor, which Thompson als=
o notes:

( https://x.com/DKThomp/status/1888288368523428209 )

There are many of these things the NBA can't replicate, at least without fu=
ndamentally reworking and slimming down its revenue model. All that, though=
, is less important than the inescapable reality that the NFL increasingly =
stands alone as a mass market product, while everything else is becoming a =
niche. That, by extension, means the NFL can simply do what it does =E2=80=
=94 show games =E2=80=94 while complementary industries like podcasts or ta=
lk shows or whatever else do what they do. It's not clear that the NBA can =
or should follow the same path.

