imum, the pie isn=E2=80=99t really growing anymore: the big question is jus=
t how much it is shrinking.

Given that, the totally logical response is consolidation first, and a focu=
s on increasing share of spend second. EMC makes total sense in that regard=
. Specifically, Dell=E2=80=99s storage business is relatively weak, so EMC=
=E2=80=99s core business increases Dell=E2=80=99s ability to make a full-st=
ack offering to enterprises who want to remain on-premise. Moreover, given =
that a company=E2=80=99s data is probably the thing many companies=E2=80=99=
 are most hesitant about moving to the public cloud, it is arguable that EM=
C=E2=80=99s high-end data business will be the incumbent most able to resis=
t AWS. To that end this acquisition seems to be Dell=E2=80=99s best attempt=
 at owning everything AWS doesn=E2=80=99t take. True AWS may take everythin=
g in the long run, but if that=E2=80=99s the case Dell is screwed anyway.

That acquisition worked out spectacularly for Dell, and it's an interesting=
 way to think about what longstanding entertainment entities like the NBA m=
ight want to consider as they face the onslaught of a truly dizzying array =
of entertainment choices facing the modern consumer. In this perspective AW=
S is TikTok/video games/YouTube/social media/even nichier sports etc. What =
does consolidation mean in this context?

In the short term, it certainly means one last payout from the cable bundle=
, which the NBA has achieved; in the longer term, might the NBA want to acq=
uire all of the independent media that has grown up around it to enhance a =
subscription offering? Collectively bargain which social media network all =
of its players are going to use? I'm not saying any of these are good ideas=
, but it is an interesting angle to think about.

Netflix to Bid on F1?
---------------------

From The Times of London ( https://www.thetimes.com/sport/formula-one/artic=
le/netflix-considering-bid-for-formula-1-tv-rights-9xd50qlm6 ) :

Netflix is considering a bid to cash in on the success of its Drive to Surv=
ive series by trying to secure the US broadcast rights to Formula 1. It wou=
ld be the first significant foray into buying season-long mainstream sports=
 rights by the streaming platform, but there has been huge growth in F1 fan=
 numbers in the United States =E2=80=94 which has three of the 24 F1 races =
=E2=80=94 and the rights would be relatively cheap. ESPN holds the rights a=
t the moment under a $90 million (=C2=A372.5 million) deal, but it is under=
stood that the broadcaster=E2=80=99s exclusivity period to negotiate a new =
contract with F1 has just expired, which has opened the market for bids fro=
m any other interested party. Industry sources have said that Netflix is ex=
pected to bid for the rights starting from the 2026 season=E2=80=A6

Other platforms such as Apple have also been linked with bidding for the F1=
 rights, and ESPN could also come back in despite failing to agree to a ren=
ewal deal during its exclusivity period. Apple has the global rights for Ma=
jor League Soccer but sources close to the process said it was highly unlik=
ely that F1 would entertain a worldwide rights deal, as selling to individu=
al territories works better for the sport.

I actually asked Netflix co-CEO Greg Peters about this last year in a Strat=
echery Interview ( https://stratechery.com/2024/an-interview-with-netflix-c=
